I would 't be optimistic about the @variable persisting from one dbSendQuery call to the next. But maybe it will.

However, I think it likely you can achieve the same result on the R side, i.e., by defining an R variable to take the place of the @variable, and then using paste() to construct the subsequent queries.

Other than that, the rest of your steps look just like what I have done from time to time. My guess would be like Sean's, a permissions issue.

I use
  dbExistsTable()
and
  dbDropTable()
instead of dbSendQuery() when I need to drop a table if it exists.

-Don

